	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Adding value through eco-labelling: lessons from South Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> In May 2004, the South African hake-trawl fishery qualified for <i>Marine Stewardship Council (</i>MSC) accreditation as being sustainably managed. The MSC is an eco-labelling initiative launched by two international organisations of global significance: the international conservation organisation, the <i>World-Wide Fund for Nature </i>(WWF) and the multi-national industrial giant Unileve <i>r</i>.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> South African hake-industry interests hope that MSC accreditation will ease market access and add value to their products in the USA and EU. The director of one of South Africa’s largest hake producers, Irving and Johnston (I&amp;J) observed that: &quot;the MSC's eco-label [will] help gain entry into new international markets. This in turn would also mean the creation of additional jobs for South Africans and maximum returns on the country's valuable hake resource.?</p><p> In September 2003, the FAO held an expert consultation on international guidelines for fishery eco-labelling. Their report, adopted in October 2003, addresses the special requirements of developing countries and countries in transition to adopt ecolabelling of fish and fishery products.</p><p>
 In February 2004 the ninth session of the FAO's sub-committee on fish trade recommended that the FAO organise a technical consultation to finalise guidelines on the use of eco-labels for the conservation of fishery resources. This will conclude the work already carried out, and will issue draft guidelines for approval by the FAO’s 187 member states. The finalised guidelines will serve as a global benchmark for eco-labelling schemes in fisheries, and the FAO will build up national capacities to implement them.<br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.cbn.co.za/issue/4190403.htm" target="_self">News article in Cape Business News</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2004/37347/index.html" target="_self">Meeting of the FAO sub-committee on trade</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/DOCREP/006/Y4941E/y4941e00.htm#Contents" target="_self">Report of the FAO meeting October 2003</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Given increasing levels of competition with non-ACP products for accessing lucrative EU (and other) markets, ACP fish products may stand to benefit from eco-labelling schemes. These could both add value to their products and facilitate market access. The benefits from such schemes need to weighed against the costs of accreditation, which may be significant. They also need to ensure that any scheme adopted has wide credibility.</p><p> The MSC is the only third-party eco-labelling scheme for marine fisheries that is global in scope. However, recent criticism of the MSC accreditation process has undermined its credibility and may cause confusion amongst consumers. It is hoped that the FAO initiative to establish guidelines may lead to more objective third-party schemes that can be trusted by consumers, and provide the necessary credibility for the users.</p><p> It is therefore important that ACP countries participate fully in the FAO process to establish eco-labelling guidelines, and ensure that developing-country concerns are fully taken into account.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

